  "prompt": "If you were born deaf, what language would you think in?",
  "response": "If someone is born deaf and has never been exposed to spoken language, they typically think in terms of visual-spatial concepts or in the sign language they have learned. For example, a Deaf person who uses American Sign Language (ASL) often thinks in ASL, using the signs and grammar of that language in their mind.  \n\nThoughts can also take the form of visual imagery, tactile sensations, or abstract concepts, depending on the individual's experiences and how they process information. Deaf individuals often develop highly visual and spatial ways of thinking, leveraging their strengths in other sensory domains.\n\nIf a Deaf person has not been exposed to any formal language (spoken or signed), their thoughts might be more abstract and non-linguistic, relying heavily on sensory and experiential information. However, language\u2014whether signed or written\u2014greatly enhances thought structure and complexity.",
